comparisons between the current year and

61
00:03:27.200 --> 00:03:28.660
the prior year.

62
00:03:28.660 --> 00:03:32.728
So the first ratio is days
sales receivable index or DSRI.

63
00:03:32.728 --> 00:03:36.760
This is gonna be days receivable divided
by prior days receivable, where days

64
00:03:36.760 --> 00:03:39.720
receivable is defined a little bit
differently than we did it in the past.

65
00:03:39.720 --> 00:03:42.550
It's receivables divided
by sales times 365.

66
00:03:42.550 --> 00:03:45.970
An increase in this could
suggest revenue manipulation.

67
00:03:46.980 --> 00:03:52.070
The Gross Margin Index, or GMI, is prior
gross margin divided by gross margin,

68
00:03:52.070 --> 00:03:55.719
where gross margin again is sales minus
cost of good sold divided by sales.

69
00:03:56.820 --> 00:03:59.880
This is gonna flag deteriorating
earnings prospects,

70
00:03:59.880 --> 00:04:02.850
which may create an incentive to
manipulate earnings during a period.

71
00:04:04.460 --> 00:04:07.490
Next is an asset quality index, AQI.

72
00:04:07.490 --> 00:04:10.610
This is asset quality divided
by prior asset quality,

73
00:04:10.610 --> 00:04:15.100
where asset quality is total assets minus
the sum of current assets and PP&E,

74
00:04:15.100 --> 00:04:17.320
all divided by total assets.

75
00:04:17.320 --> 00:04:21.380
This is intended to measure soft assets or
intangible assets, for

76
00:04:21.380 --> 00:04:24.010
which the realization of
benefits is uncertain.

77
00:04:24.010 --> 00:04:28.450
For example, they could suggest
excessive capitalization of costs,

78
00:04:28.450 --> 00:04:30.420
as we saw in the expense
recognition videos.

79
00:04:31.900 --> 00:04:36.880
Sales growth index, or SGI,
is gonna be sales over prior sales.

80
00:04:36.880 --> 00:04:40.370
So growth companies often face
pressure to meet earnings targets and

81
00:04:40.370 --> 00:04:44.940
